[1] Taiwan: nosocomial, ex Viet Nam
Date: Thu 27 Jun 2019 21:21:22 CST
Source: Focus Taiwan News Channel, Central News Agency (CNA) report [edited]
http://focustaiwan.tw/news/asoc/201906270019.aspx


The Centers for Disease Control (CDC) on [Thu 27 Jun 2019] confirmed one new case of measles in Taiwan, saying the patient had contracted the infection at a hospital.

The 7-month-old boy was at the emergency room of a hospital in central 8-9 Jun 2019, at the same time as a 1-year-old girl who had measles, the CDC said.

The boy was taken back to the hospital [Thu 27 Jun 2019] after he developed a rash on [21 Jun 2019], and follow-up tests confirmed that he was infected with the same strain of measles as the girl, the CDC said.

The girl is believed to have contracted measles during a visit to Viet Nam in March 2019, according to the CDC.

So far, 510 people who had contact with the 2 children have been identified and will be monitored by health authorities through [15 Jul 2019], the CDC said.

At the hospital, all personnel who have not been vaccinated against measles will be required to obtain the measles-mumps-rubella (MMR) vaccine, CDC Deputy Director-General Chuang Jen-hsiang said.

So far this year [2019], there have been 101 confirmed cases of measles in Taiwan -- 66 locally acquired and 35 imported, according to CDC data.

Thailand, Viet Nam, and the Philippines are the top 3 sources of measles infections among Taiwanese, according to the CDC.

[Byline: Flor Wang, Chen Wei-ting]

