[4] USA (Seattle, Washington)
Date: Fri 28 Jun 2019 5:49 PM PDT
Source: The Seattle Times [abridged, edited]
https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/eighth-case-of-measles-in-king-county-residents-exposure-at-seattle-childrens/


King county public health officials announced another confirmed case of measles on [Fri 28 Jun 2019] and warned that anyone who visited Seattle Children's emergency room or a Fred Meyer [hypermarket superstores] in Kent on certain days may have been exposed.

The child who was recently diagnosed is the 8th resident in King county to contract measles since the beginning of the year[2019], according to Public Health-Seattle & King County. The case is the 10th in Western Washington since an outbreak was declared in May [2019].

The child was at a Fred Meyer in Kent last week [week of 17 Jun 2019] and at Seattle Children's twice this week before being diagnosed, according to Public Health. Seattle Children's says they are notifying visitors and patients who may have been exposed.

Health officials are still working to determine the source of the child's measles and whether this case is connected to others in the area. Last month [May 2019], an infant was diagnosed with measles after she was brought to Seattle Children's emergency department.

The Western Washington measles outbreak began on 9 May 2019, with residents of Pierce, King, and Snohomish counties diagnosed after spending time at the Seattle-Tacoma International Airport.

This year [2019], Washington has had 82 cases, or about 8% of the 1077 cases reported in the United States, which prompted state lawmakers to ban exemptions to the measles, mumps, and rubella vaccine except for religious or medical reasons. Most of the state's cases were from a Clark county outbreak earlier this year.

This year [2019], the US has seen the most cases since 1992 and since measles was declared eliminated in 2000, according to the federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC).

A full list of exposure sites in King county can be found on Public Health's website at https://kingcounty.gov/depts/health/communicable-diseases/disease-control/measles/cases.aspx.

[Byline: Asia Fields]

