[6] UK (Wimbledon, England)
Date: Sat 29 Jul 2019
Source: Vax Before Travel [abridged, edited]
https://www.vaxbeforetravel.com/are-djokovic-federer-and-nadal-protected-london-measles-outbreak


When the All England Lawn Tennis and Croquet Club hosts over 450 000 tennis fans between 1-13 Jul 2019, are patrons being required to present measles immunization proof prior to entry?

This question is relevant since 'The Championships, Wimbledon' is taking place in one of the world's measles hot-spots.

Measles is so contagious that if one person has it, up to 90 percent of the under-vaccinated people 'sitting' close to that person who are not immune, will also become infected.

During the 1st quarter of 2019, there were 231 confirmed cases of measles in the United Kingdom (UK). Which follows the 971 confirmed cases in 2018.

Specifically, the ongoing measles outbreak in greater London is primarily occurring in under-vaccinated communities, particularly those with links to other countries with ongoing measles outbreaks, such as France (1749) over the past year.

Alternatively, Wimbledon could offer its tennis patrons access to on-campus measles vaccination services.

A recent case-study for Wimbledon to emulate is the Indianapolis 500 race last May, which offered its 300 000 patrons easy access to on-campus, vaccination clinics.

[Byline: Dani Reiter]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Free measles vaccination clinics at sporting events, especially those where families might attend, is an excellent approach. It would be interesting to know how many vaccinations were given at the Indy500 race referred to above. - Mod.LK

